Introduction¶

In this project, I'll explore the TMDb dataset which contains data releted to movies. Each movie in this dataset has data related to ratings, budget, genre, cast and many other details.

In the first part of the exploration, I'll try to investigate the relationship between genre and other properties like revenue, popolarity, runtime, budget etc. I'll try to find out how revenue, budget, popularity, runtime etc varies according to the genre of the movie. This will be single variable (1d) explorations where genre will be the independent variables and I'll try to find trends in other properties when we vary genre. Then, I'll investigate, the popularity value of a movie over genre and release year (2d exploration) hoping to find interesting trends in the popularity value over the years for each genre. In all these explorations I'll average the value of interest over the genres. e.g., the average value of revenue for each genre. In my opinion the average seems to give a better estimate than the sum or other aggregate functions because the number of movies in a particular genre may be very high and calculating the sum would make it way bigger than other genres, thus leading to wrong interpretations.

In the second part of the exploration, I'll investigate the properties of a high revenue movie, specifically, how the revenue varies with other properties like average vote, number of votes, popularity etc. I'll also investigate how the average revenue varies over the years and if there is any relationship between average rating, average vote count, average popularity and revenue over the years.

At the end, I'll do some analysis of runtime and average rating.

Then there are other properties like the original title, cast, homepage, director, tagline, overview. It also has budget and revenue information based on 2010 dollar values which may be of help when we want to remove the effect of inflation over the years.

# function to find out the full list of genres
def full_list_of_genres(genres):
    '''
    This function takes the genres column of the dataframe and 
    returns the full list of genres of all the movies in dataset
    '''
    genres_str = genres.values.tolist()
    genre_list = []
    for i in genres_str:
        split_genres = i.split('|')
        for j in split_genres:
            if j not in genre_list:
                genre_list.append(j)
    return genre_list

# Get the full list of genres
genres = full_list_of_genres(df['genres'])

Now, I'll create a new dataframe which will have all the genre information against a particular movie. I'll go through the whole list of movies and find out the genres and put a 1 in the columns corresponding to the genre the movie belongs to. Then I'll merge the genre dataframe with the original dataframe on imdb_id and create a new dataframe which have the consolidated information.

genre_df = pd.DataFrame(index=range(len(df)) ,columns=genres)
genre_df = genre_df.fillna(value=0)

# fill up the genre df with genre info of each movie
for i in range(len(df)):
    genre_list = df.iloc[i]['genres'].split('|')
    genre_df.loc[i, 'imdb_id'] = df.iloc[i]['imdb_id']
    for j in genre_list:
        genre_df.loc[i, j] = 1

In [11]:
# Get the list of all genres
genres = full_list_of_genres(tmdb_df['genres'])

# Generic function to plot the distribution over genre
def distribution_over_genre(var):
    '''
    This function takes a variable name and plots the 
    distribution of that variable over genre on a bar chart
    '''
    distribution_var = pd.Series(index=genres)
    for genre in genres:
        distribution_var[genre] = tmdb_df.groupby([genre]).mean()[var][1]
    title = 'Distribution of '+ var +' over genre'
    distribution_var.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(20, 5), title=title)
    plt.show()

This is a generic utility code to plot the distribution of a particular field over genre. I'll use this below to plot the distribution as will be shown below.

Documentary, Foreign, TV Movies, Western: Not popular

In conclusion, Action, Adventure, Thriller, Drama, Family, Comedy, Ramance genres are all time favorits. Horror movies were very popular since early 70s but recently the popularity dropped. Documentary, Foreign, TV Movies, Western are not popular throughout.

Now, I'll investigate how the revenue varies with other parameters. First, I'll investigate how average revenue varies acroos genre.

In [23]:
years = sorted(tmdb_df['release_year'].unique(), reverse=True)

# utility function plot distribution of data over years
def distribution_var_years(var):
    '''
    This function takes a variable as input and plots the distribution 
    of that variable over years
    '''
    distribution_years = pd.Series(index=years)
    for year in years:
        distribution_years[year] = tmdb_df.groupby('release_year').mean()[var][year]
    title = 'Distribution of ' + var + ' over years'
    distribution_years.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(20, 5), title = title)
    plt.show()
In [24]:
# plot distribution of revenue over years
distribution_var_years('revenue')

# plot distribution of revenue_adj over years
distribution_var_years('revenue_adj')

The first plot above shows revenue acroos the years and it seems that after 90s the average revenue seeems to a lot more than previous years. But the second plot above shows the complete opposite. This is actually a very good insight. Becuase the earlier plot was on revenue field, and the later one is on revenue_adj which is more appropriate as it combines the inflation information over the years. So, in my opinion, using revenue_adj is more appropriate measure of revenue. I'll use revenue_adj in future plots.

# utility function to create scatter plot of var1 and var2
def plot_scatter(x_var, y_var):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.scatter(np.array(tmdb_df[x_var]), np.array(tmdb_df[y_var]))
    plt.title('Scatter plot of ' + x_var + ' vs ' + y_var)
    plt.xlabel(x_var)
    plt.ylabel(y_var)
    plt.show()

# utility function to create scatter plot of var1 and var2
def plot_scatter_years(x_var, y_var):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,4))
    plt.scatter(np.array(years_df[x_var]), np.array(years_df[y_var]))
    plt.title('Scatter plot of ' + x_var + ' vs ' + y_var)
    plt.xlabel(x_var)
    plt.ylabel(y_var)
    plt.show()
    
plot_scatter_years('popularity', 'revenue')
plot_scatter_years('vote_count', 'revenue')
plot_scatter_years('vote_average', 'revenue')

Limitations and Further Scope¶

  1. This study doesn't check how the various mesaures are computed like popularity, vote_count, vote_average. They are considered same as their face value intuitively suggegsting that higher the measures are the higher is the value of that metric.
  2. Revenue models also are not researched. Like revenue can be measures in terms of ticket sales, broadcase profits etc. But those are not researched in details.
  3. Whenever the study suggests a trend, it is due to the observational statistics. No statistical test has been done to infer anything. Also, whenever a possible cause is cited, it is cited in an informal manner and should be considered as an educated guess.
  4. No statement imply causation. For causation, we need to perform experiments which is not done here.
  5. There were a lot of data in this dataset which are not used in the analysis like cast, keywords, director etc. I strongly think that very useful informartion can be found if those properties are investigated in detail.

Conclusions¶

This completes the exploration of the dataset. I did all the relevant discussion at the end of each analysis step, so not repeating it again. I found useful information and trends in the data which can be used to predict the popularity or may be the revenue of future movies before they are even released.
